snippet.textDisplay:
I think the thing that made Rick go to pieces was that he was unable to box the cat in and was aware he's never going to take back nor prevent useless violence (that Rick hates so much) this cat' s going to make-it's too powerful or for some reason unstopable. Just think about it; Rick is capable of traveling in time, trough dimensions and different realities. He is capable of changing the patch of evolution. He could've made this cat actually never being born. I'm sure he calculated all the posibillities and chances. Yet he was doomed to never change the situation, because he knew, no matter what means would be used it would never helped or made it even worse. If he killed the cat it would made it worse(maybe more pointless violence caused by Butterfly effect etc?)so banish him was the best action to take in these circumstances. Maybe it was coincidence or maybe it was planned by that creature-to change the reality that it can never be used against him. If this is true, it would be SO crucial to the structure of the show's reality-it demolish Infinite Monkey Theorem which states that given enough time(e.g. Infinity or infinite amount of chances) anything would randomly happen( I don't know if I understand it properly though.) that most of Rick's solutions are based on and he couldn't predict he would know he can't do everything - Whatever happened, was the proof that some things Rick is unable to control, some stuff he just can't overcome despite he desperately wants to.
I think that's the thing that broke him. ( Maybe he discovered this knowledge not for the first time?)
I am probably overthinking or made it too complicated but if you think about for a minute it is terryfing but makes sense.

snippet.textDisplay: I think you may have missed the specifics. It wasn't just a bad incident in his past, but it's the reason he can talk. Ultimately him talking would serve as a reminder of this event. I personally believe it's someone making a cross between a cat and a human in the um...old fashioned way. Another issue though is that the cat himself keeps bringing the issue up. Saying "don't ask about it" is guaranteed to make people curious. I think what the cat wants is for someone to ask him and accept him. These ideas fall in line with Rick not killing him. He was created as a result of an event, but not the actual cause.

snippet.textDisplay:
I disagree with the notion that answers are negative, for example Star wars- yes I am one of those who dislikes the sequels for leaving room to speculate and giving annoying answers, but I liked exploring Han Solo backstory, I love Solo as the best of Star Wars(specifically films), if we didn't have Anakin's backstory detailed then I wouldn't see the only good acting from Jake Lloyd when leaving Shmi Skywalker. if I never had Solo a Star Wars story then i wouldn't see the pristine Millennium Falcon, or Maul. it is not that answers are always unsatisfying but that some are badly written, like Rey's story.
I am on Rick Sanchez' side all the way.

snippet.textDisplay:
@The Film Theorists Awesome episode!! Along the lines of what you said about the fun in picking things apart or theorizing just to do so - I watch most of the episodes on both of these channels even though I've never played most of the games (Minecraft for example) the theories on the other channel are about and likewise have never seen many of focuses for this channel's episodes (i.e. I've only watch a handful of R & M episodes). And yet I really enjoy the theories and looking into the lore of the games and films and so on. I'm a fan of philosophy and other things and so the act of pulling things apart and/or investigating them through questioning is endlessly entertaining and stimulating to me. Additionally, I have a number of difficult things I'm dealing with offline (taking care of sick parent, health problems of my own) that for now have my life kinda locked in, and so to have things like your channels - and all the others I watch and enjoy - gives me something to wrap my brain around that for a number of hours a day (or in this case 4:30am on a Thurs morning when I couldn't sleep) distracts me from everything else. I'm still taking care of my responsibilities, and so I'm not avoiding them with this stuff. This just provides some breathing room, which makes everything else a little easier to take on. So, thank you.
I know I've rambled a bit here, but I'm a little old-ish and so I still haven't gotten the hang of the whole brevity-thing that is kinda expected when you post comments on YT and elsewhere online. But maybe I'll get there someday. :-) **Amended: Lol - thanks to my ADD I didn't think about this until after I'd posted the comment. But I wanted to make very clear that the info above is not meant to be a "boo hoo me" or "I want sympathy" bit. My only reason for providing those details was just to explain the reason for my gratitude - that's all. Okie doke, just needed to amend that or it would keep nagging me.
My actual comment about the episode (I know, finally lol) is below:

This may be reading into it further than necessary but - what about the fact that their response to seeing something so terrible that it makes them physically ill is to just tell it to go away? Out of sight, out of mind. Is that really the best way to deal with the worst of the worlds problems - the ones that make you want to curl up in the fetal position in your bed? Their response to this terribly offensive/repulsive/disgusting sight - whatever it was - was to simply push it away and not think about it again. I haven't seen the episode and so I don't know where the show went from there right after that happened. If they actually did something to try to discuss and/or process what they had seen or if that plotline just ended there with them closing their minds to it as their way of coping.
I'm assuming this isn't the message they were trying to get across with that choice, but since we're picking the episode apart I thought it might be worth poking this question too. What is the best way to address something you experience that triggers that level of revulsion? If it was something particularly bad -are they turning it loose for someone else to have to run into as well? Is it something that maybe they could have helped the cat move on from by talking it out? In spite of there being something pretty awful in the cat's past - clearly there doesn't seem to be any empathy expressed or shown for the cat by the characters. So is part of closing our eyes or minds off to terrible things - also condemning anything that happens to be associated with those things to facing them alone?
